  "prompt": "What is the function of right dorsolateral prefrontal cortex?",
  "response": "The **right dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC)** is a region in the prefrontal cortex that plays a critical role in higher-order cognitive functions, particularly those involving **executive control**, **working memory**, **attention**, and **goal-directed behavior**. Its specific functions include:\n\n1. **Executive Functions**:\n   - Planning, organizing, and initiating complex tasks.\n   - Problem-solving and decision-making.\n   - Inhibitory control, such as suppressing inappropriate or impulsive responses.\n\n2. **Working Memory**:\n   - Temporarily holding and manipulating information necessary for cognitive tasks.\n   - Integrating and processing information from different sources to guide behavior.\n\n3. **Attention and Cognitive Control**:\n   - Sustaining attention on tasks and shifting focus when necessary.\n   - Monitoring and updating information in response to changing demands.\n\n4. **Emotional Regulation**:\n   - Modulating emotional responses and integrating cognitive and emotional processes.\n   - Helping to regulate negative emotions and reduce stress-related reactivity.\n\n5. **Goal-Directed Behavior**:\n   - Setting and maintaining goals.\n   - Monitoring progress toward goals and adjusting behavior accordingly.\n\nThe right DLPFC is particularly involved in tasks requiring **spatial attention**, **non-verbal reasoning**, and **self-regulation**. Dysfunction in this area is associated with conditions such as **ADHD**, **depression**, and **executive dysfunction** in various neurological disorders. Neuromodulation techniques like **transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS)** targeting this region are sometimes used in treatment for these conditions.",
